{{Expand German|Alfred Merz|date=December 2009}} {{Infobox scientist | name = Alfred Merz | image = Alfred Merz.jpg | image_size = <!-- 300px --> | caption = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1880|1|24|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Perchtoldsdorf]], [[Niederösterreich]], [[Austria]] | death_date = {{death date and age|1925|8|16|1880|1|24|df=y}} | death_place = [[Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]] | residence = {{GER}} | nationality = {{AUT}} | field = [[Geography]], [[Oceanography]] | work_institution = Institute of Marine Science, Berlin | alma_mater = University of Vienna | doctoral_advisor = | doctoral_students = | known_for = | prizes = }} '''Alfred Merz''' (24 January 1880 in [[Perchtoldsdorf]], [[Niederösterreich]] &ndash; 16 August 1925 in [[Buenos Aires]]) was an [[Austria]]n [[geographer]], [[oceanographer]] and director of the Institute of Marine Science in Berlin. He died of pneumonia in Buenos Aires while on an expedition to survey the South Atlantic and is buried in Perchtoldsdorf.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.bsh.de/de/Meeresnutzung/Wissenschaft/Forschungsschiffe/Schiffseinsatzplaene/Meteor_1924_1939.jsp|title = Geschichte der ersten Meteor|author = |date = 10 March 2011|work = www.bsh.de|publisher = [[Bundesamt für Seeschifffahrt und Hydrographie]] (German Maritime and Hydrographic Agency)|language = German|trans-title = History of the first Meteor|accessdate = 6 April 2013|quote = shortend version from: Fritz Nieder, Willy Schroeder: Seevermessung - 25 Jahre im Deutschen Hydrographischen Institut (1945-1970), DHI, Hamburg 1971|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081208033808/http://www.bsh.de/de/Meeresnutzung/Wissenschaft/Forschungsschiffe/Schiffseinsatzplaene/Meteor_1924_1939.jsp|archive-date = 2008-12-08|dead-url = yes|df = }}</ref><ref>[http://markt-perchtoldsdorf.at/index.php?option=com_content&catid=1&task=view&id=21&ASCDESC=ASC&ad_type=0&Itemid=79&p=p Great People of Perchtoldsdorf] Verified 2011-01-24.</ref> [[Merz Peninsula]] is named after him.
