{{Other uses}} {{globalize|date=August 2018}}
[[File:ManchesterCity With Ferris.jpg|thumb|Inner city Manchester, England, 2007]]
In the [[United Kingdom]] the term "inner city" has been used as a euphemism for lower-income residential districts in the [[city center]] and nearby areas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/bitesize/higher/geography/human/urban/revision/4/|title=BBC - Higher Bitesize Geography - Urban : Revision, Page4|author=|date=|website=bbc.co.uk|accessdate=7 April 2018}}</ref> Sociologists sometimes turn this euphemism into a formal designation, applying the term "inner city" to such residential areas, rather than to geographically more [[Central business district|central commercial districts]]. Some inner city areas of American cities have undergone [[gentrification]], especially since the 1990s.<ref name=governing>{{cite web|url=http://www.brookings.edu/~/media/Files/Programs/Metro/state_of_metro_america/metro_america_chapters/metro_america_race.pdf|title=''State of Metropolitan America'', Part II, "Race and Ethnicity"|p=62|author=|date=|website=brookings.edu|accessdate=7 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100530113853/http://www.brookings.edu/~/media/Files/Programs/Metro/state_of_metro_america/metro_america_chapters/metro_america_race.pdf|archive-date=30 May 2010|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}} ([[Brookings Institution]]) and its analysis in {{cite web|last=Gurwitt|first=Rob|url=http://www.governing.com/topics/politics/Atlanta-and-the-Urban.html|title=Atlanta and the Urban Future|date=July 2008|work=[[Governing (magazine)|Governing]]|accessdate=April 5, 2010}} — see example in [[Demographics of Atlanta#Race and ethnicity|Demographics of Atlanta: Race and ethnicity]]</ref>
