[[Image:Line5318_-_Flickr_-_NOAA_Photo_Library.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Pago Pago Harbor is capable of accommodating the largest ships in the world.<ref>https://americansamoatourism.com/pago-pago-harbor-american-samoa</ref><ref>https://www.cruiseindustrynews.com/cruise-news/17229-american-samoa-targets-expedition-market.html</ref><ref>http://traveltips.usatoday.com/american-samoa-cruises-18066.html</ref>]] [[Image:Fagatogo Dock.jpg|right|300px|thumb|A portion of the docks at [[Fagatogo]] in Pago Pago Harbor. In the background is [[Rainmaker Mountain]].]] '''Pago Pago Harbor''' on [[Tutuila Island]] in [[American Samoa]] is one of the world's largest [[natural harbor]]s.<ref>https://ngdc.noaa.gov/mgg/coastal/pacific_islands_dem_catalog.pdf</ref> The capital, [[Pago Pago]] is located on the inner reaches of the harbor, close to its northwesternmost point. It has the highest annual rainfall of any harbor in the world.<ref>https://www.lonelyplanet.com/american-samoa/tutuila/attractions/rainmaker-mountain/a/poi-sig/1456093/362248</ref> It is also considered one of the best and deepest deepwater harbors in the [[South Pacific Ocean]] or in [[Oceania]] as a whole.<ref>United States Central Intelligence Agency (2016). ''The World Factbook 2016-17''. Government Printing Office. Page 19. {{ISBN|9780160933271}}.</ref><ref>Grabowski, John F. (1992). ''U.S. Territories and Possessions (State Report Series)''. Chelsea House Pub. Page 52. {{ISBN|9780791010532}}.</ref><ref>Kristen, Katherine (1999). ''Pacific Islands (Portrait of America)''. San Val. Page 12. {{ISBN|9780613032421}}.</ref>
Villages along the harbor include several communities in the Greater Pago Pago Area, including [[Utulei, American Samoa|Utulei]], [[Fagatogo]], [[Malaloa]], [[Pago Pago|Pago Pago proper]], [[Satala, American Samoa|Satala]], [[Anua, American Samoa|Anua]] and [[Atu'u, American Samoa|Atu'u]]. The judicial capital is Fagotago, while the legislative capital is Utulei.{{cn|date=October 2017}}
Pago Pago Harbor is surrounded and sheltered by mountains such as Mount Alava, [[Mount Matafao]] and [[Rainmaker Mountain]] (Mount Pioa).<ref>http://americansamoaport.as.gov/</ref>
==Tsunami== [[Fagatogo]] was struck by a [[tsunami]] on 29 September 2009, causing damage and [[rock slide]]s.<ref>[https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5gcQYRcaxXR6t5UcX_WlbD_qBAmQwD9B16T6G0] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091003024511/https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5gcQYRcaxXR6t5UcX_WlbD_qBAmQwD9B16T6G0 |date=October 3, 2009 }}</ref> A significant amount of [[debris]] and [[oil]] were dumped into Pago Pago Harbor during the [[2009 Samoa earthquake and tsunami]], which devastated communities along the harbor's coastline, including [[Pago Pago]].<ref name=samoanews>{{cite news|first=|last=|title=Coral Reef Advisory tsunami report focuses on extensive marine and coastal debris |url=http://www.samoanews.com/viewstory.php?storyid=9718&edition=1254909600 |work=[[Samoa News]]|publisher=|date=2009-10-07 |accessdate=2009-10-07}}</ref> Debris including cars, household items, and boats were thrown into the harbor by the force of the wave.<ref name=samoanews/> According to the 14-page American Samoan government report, ''Post-Tsunami Coastal Resource Damage Assessment'', "The inner section of Pago Pago Harbor is severely [[polluted]] and will require an extensive cleanup program with a significant amount of manpower ... The destruction is everywhere."<ref name=samoanews/>
An [[oil spill]] approximately 40 feet wide occurred at the mouth of Pago Pago Harbor as a result of the tsunami.<ref name=samoanews/> Barrels containing fuel were thrown into the harbor by the tsunami and washed up on shore.<ref name=samoanews/>
It is suggested that one must avoid eating any fish or invertebrate caught in Pago Pago Harbor because they are contaminated with heavy metals and other pollutants.<ref> {{cite web | url = http://www.nps.gov/archive/npsa/book/04_local.htm | title = Natural History Guide To American Samoa | accessdate = 2007-02-16 | publisher = nps.org }}</ref>
