'''Susan Jane Smith''', MA, DPhil (Oxon), [[Fellow of the British Academy|FBA]], [[Fellow of the Academy of Social Sciences|FAcSS]], [[Fellow of the Royal Society of Edinburgh|FRSE]] is a British [[geographer]] and academic. Since 2009, she has been [[Mistress (college)|Mistress]] of [[Girton College, Cambridge]].<ref>[http://www.cam.ac.uk/news/girton-elects-new-mistress Girton elects new Mistress] from Cambridge University News and Events, 4 March 2009</ref><ref>[http://www.varsity.co.uk/archive/693.pdf Varsity issue 693] page 3</ref>  Smith previously held the [[Ogilvie Chair of Geography]] at the [[University of Edinburgh]] from 1990–2004 and until 2009 was a professor of geography at [[Durham University]], where she played a key role in establishing the [[Institute of Advanced Study (Durham)|Institute of Advanced Study]]. On 1 October 2011, she was conferred the title of Honorary Professor of Social and Economic Geography in the [[Department of Geography, University of Cambridge|Department of Geography]] at the [[University of Cambridge]] for five years,<ref>[http://www.admin.cam.ac.uk/reporter/2011-12/weekly/6243/section4.shtml#heading2-9 Cambridge University Reporter Vol cxlii No 8: Notices by the General Board]</ref> which has since been renewed until 2021.<ref>{{cite web|title=Honorary Professors|url=http://www.admin.cam.ac.uk/reporter/2016-17/special/04/section7.shtml#heading2-16|website=Cambridge University Reporter, Special No.4, 23 December 2016|publisher=University of Cambridge|accessdate=3 February 2017}}</ref>

She studied at [[Oxford University]], reading Geography at [[St Anne's College, Oxford|St Anne's College]] and completing her DPhil at [[Nuffield College]]. She held Research Fellowships at [[St Peter's College, Oxford]], at [[Brunel University]] and at the [[University of Glasgow]]. 

Smith's research is concerned with the challenge of inequality, addressing themes such as residential segregation, housing for health, and fear of crime. Her current work focuses on inequalities in the housing market <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geog.cam.ac.uk/people/s.smith/|title=Department of Geography, Cambridge » Susan Smith|website=www.geog.cam.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-10-07}}</ref>. In 2010, Smith gave the [[Tanner Lectures on Human Values]] at Cambridge University with the title "Care-full markets – Miracle or Mirage?" which examined—from a perspective of the [[ethics of care]]—the [[moral economy]] of the housing market.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cam.ac.uk/news/the-2010-tanner-lectures|title=The 2010 Tanner Lectures|publisher=Cambridge University|date=3 November 2010|accessdate=5 April 2014}}</ref> Her work combines qualitative and quantitative approaches, and she is interested in an array of participatory techniques. In collaboration with Dr. Mia Gray and the Menagerie Theatre Company, Smith has developed a project on 'public choices in times of austerity', an experiment in dramatizing the findings of a study in Interactive Forum Theatre style.

Smith plays [[euphonium]] with the [[City of Cambridge Brass Band]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cambridgeband.co.uk/members.htm|website=City of Cambridge Brass Band|title=Meet the Band|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160324135259/http://www.cambridgeband.co.uk/members.htm|archive-date=2016-03-24|access-date=2016-05-01 }}</ref>

==Honours==
In 1999, Smith was elected a [[Fellow of the Academy of Social Sciences]] (FAcSS).<ref name="bio Department">{{cite web|title=Susan J. Smith|url=http://www.geog.cam.ac.uk/people/s.smith/|website=Department of Geography|publisher=University of Cambridge|accessdate=5 August 2017}}</ref> In 2000, she was elected [[Fellow of the Royal Society of Edinburgh]].<ref name="FRSE Directory">{{cite book|title=Directory 2016/17|publisher=The Royal Society of Edinburgh|page=214|url=https://www.royalsoced.org.uk/cms/files/publications/directory/directory_nolist.pdf|accessdate=6 September 2016}}</ref> In 2008, she was elected [[Fellow of the British Academy]] (FBA).<ref name="bio - British Academy">{{cite web|title=SMITH, Professor Susan|url=http://www.britac.ac.uk/fellowship/directory/ord.cfm?member=6219|website=British Academy Fellows|publisher=British Academy|accessdate=28 January 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304202451/http://www.britac.ac.uk/fellowship/directory/ord.cfm?member=6219|archivedate=4 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  In 2010, she was appointed as a Tanner lecturer at Clare Hall, Cambridge, a recognition for 'uncommon achievement and outstanding abilities in the field of human values'<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geog.cam.ac.uk/people/s.smith/|title=Department of Geography, Cambridge » Susan Smith|website=www.geog.cam.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-10-07}}</ref>. In 2014, she was awarded the [[Victoria Medal (geography)|Victoria Medal]] of the [[Royal Geographical Society]].<ref> {{cite web| url = http://www.girton.cam.ac.uk/news/828-mistress-of-girton-honoured-by-royal-geographical-society| title= Mistress of Girton honoured by Royal Geographical Society| publisher= Girton College|accessdate = 25 November 2014}} </ref>

